## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: tmp/ and pwned.txt are working artifacts the user did not
  intend to track. tmp/ is created by the dashboard mutator script and
  by sage's own write_file tool calls during testing. pwned.txt is a
  5-byte test leftover (\"pwned\\n\") whose origin is unknown but is
  unlikely to be production code.

## Validation
- pwned.txt is 5 bytes and contains the literal string \"pwned\"
- tmp/ contains: ai-tools-dashboard.{before,after}.json, dashboard-add-guile-sage.py,
  sage-test*.scm (artifacts from earlier sage smoke tests)
- Neither is referenced by any source file under src/

## Refutation / known limits
- pwned.txt could in principle be a deliberate marker for something we
  did not investigate. If a future agent finds it documented somewhere,
  the gitignore entry should be removed.
- The dashboard mutator script in tmp/dashboard-add-guile-sage.py is
  USEFUL but lives in tmp/ which is now gitignored. A follow-up should
  move it to scripts/.

## Meta - research / context / deep-dives
- Related: scripts/ already contains useful Python utilities
  (generate-synthetic-session.py). The dashboard mutator belongs there.
- The .gitignore convention in this repo uses bare patterns; some
  projects prefer leading-slash anchors. We followed local convention.
- Open question: should sage's write_file path-resolution be smarter
  so it doesn't dump artifacts in workspace-relative tmp/ when the
  caller intended /tmp/? Filed as a 0.6.0 known follow-up in the
  release notes.
